“Our latest data highlights our sector’s enduring appeal and resilience and is recovering faster than anticipated.

“This trend underlines the longstanding consumer appetite for travel, and despite China's full recovery potential yet to be realised, the global sector’s performance is exceeding expectations.”

result.text:
📍Shri Sanatan Dharma Mandal Hindu Temple: Unfortunately closed for renovations during the time of my visit. 

📍Taxi Park: Used by over 200,000 passengers daily, this is where locals commute to/from work between Kampala and their homes on the city outskirts. 

📍The Gaddafi Mosque: It’s the biggest mosque in Uganda and can accommodate up to 20,000 people. Climbing the minaret for the views is a must! Initially built by Idi Amin in 1972, former Libyan leader Gaddafi then demolished and rebuilt it, therefore got its name. After Gaddafi’s death the mosque was renamed to Uganda National Mosque in 2013. 

📍Kabaka’s Palace Lubiri Mengo: Built in 1885, it’s the official historic residence of the Buganda King. 

📍Tombs of Buganda Kings at Kasubi: One of four UNESCO World Heritage Sites in Uganda and the only one in Kampala. The former palace of the Kabakas of Buganda was built in 1882 and converted into a royal burial ground in 1884.
